        <td valign="top" width="14%"><p align="center"><font size="2">10,1</font></td>
        <td valign="top" width="14%"><p align="center"><font size="2">7,8</font></td>
        <td valign="top" width="14%"><p align="center"><font size="2">11</font></td>
        <td valign="top" width="14%"><p align="center"><font size="2">5,6</font></td>
        <td valign="top" width="14%"><p align="center"><font size="2">7,9</font></td>
        <td valign="top" width="14%"><p align="center"><font size="2">7,6</font></td>
        <td valign="top" width="14%"><p align="center"><font size="2">6,88</font></td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    </center></div><p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">of observation when they pass to the
    adult group of athletes, they attain the least successful results during that time. There
    is some increase in the athletic result (unauthentically р &lt; 0,05) during the 5th year
    of observation, and it is approximately on the same level during the following years. The
    profile of the factor of attack reliability and the athletic result have practically the
    same trend: on the whole, they tend downwards from the young age to the adults while going
    over to the &quot;plateau&quot;, i.e. evening up, from the 5th year of observation.</font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2"><b>DISCUSSION.</b> The period of transition of juniors
    to the adult group should be noted. A decrease in the factor of attack reliability in the
    standing struggling position, a deterioration of, or reduction in, the athletic results,
    and the destruction of the pattern of activity, are obviously connected with the
    insufficient level of physical training of the former juniors, their lack of experience
    and tactical skill in the struggle by comparison with the adult bora group. Youths and
    juniors showing high performance at their age with reference to the factors of attack
    reliability and the athletic result come down henceforth, on the whole, bringing about
    worse results in the course of their further athletic improvement. </font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="2"><b>Literature List</b></font></p>
    <p style="text-indent: 40; text-align: justify"><font size="2">1.Balsevich V,K., Zaporojanov V.A. Physical activity of
